===Etymology 2===
{{zh-forms|alt=ㄉ-Taiwanese Mandarin,der-Mandarin; cute–sounding,个-Hokkien,兮-Hokkien,ㄟ-Taiwanese Hokkien,之-Classical Chinese;Hokkien,亓-Hokkien}}
First attested in the {{w|Tang Dynasty}} as {{zh-l|*底}}. This glyph was borrowed later to represent ''de'', the possessive marker in Northern Chinese, superseding the earlier {{zh-l|*底}} as a way to write this word.

There are three main competing proposals for its etymology:
* Derived from the lenition of the literary genitive marker {{och-l|之}} ({{zh-ref|Demiéville, 1950}}; {{zh-ref|Wang, 1958}}; {{zh-ref|Mei, 1988}}), which is still preserved in many phrases, and in the written form to some extent, especially in Taiwan.
* Derived from the lenition of {{och-l|者|nominalizer > medieval possessive}} ({{zh-ref|Lü, 1943}}; {{zh-ref|Yuan et al., 1996}}; {{zh-ref|Yang, R., 2016}}). Note that 的 is also a nominalizer like 者 in Classical Chinese. 
* Derived from the lenition of Middle Chinese demonstrative {{ltc-l|底}} ({{zh-ref|Shi, 2015, 2023}}).

If from either of the first two etymons, possibly cognate with the demonstrative {{zh-l|這}}. 

Possibly cognate with the particle sense of {{zh-l|*地}}, which is homophonic but now has its specialised usage.

In contemporary times it is also used to represent unrelated equivalent particles in other Chinese varieties. Examples include {{cog|nan-hbl|ê}} (variously also written as {{zh-l|*个}}, {{zh-l|*之}}, {{zh-l|*兮}}, {{zh-l|*亓}}, {{zh-l|*ㄟ}}, possibly derived from {{zh-l|*其}} according to Douglas (1873)<ref>{{R:nan:Douglas|dê|99}}</ref> although the ''Arte de la Lengua Chiõ Chiu'' (1620) and ''Dictionario Hispanico Sinicum'' (1626-1642) historically used {{zh-l|*个}}), {{cog|cdo|-}} ''gì'' ({{zh-l|*其}}), {{cog|wuu|-}} ''geq'' ({{zh-l|*個}}) and {{cog|yue|-}} ''ge<sup>3</sup>'' ({{zh-l|嘅}} < {{zh-l|*個}}).

